{"key":"post-8607541","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8607541</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;nonlinear said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;RR, can you explain why PC with stopcock is called a sterilizer, and PC with a weight is called a PC?&amp;nbsp; i understand how they are different, but why the name difference? &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A PC with a stopcock will produce a vacuum as it cools.&amp;nbsp; Any materal inside will remain completely sterile until you open the unit, hopefully in front of a laminar flowhood.&amp;nbsp; Note: New AA pressure cookers and sterilizers have a silly rubber overpressure plug that leaks when pressure reaches zero, preventing the formation of a vacuum.&amp;nbsp; I solve this by placing a sheet or two of tyvek over the rubber plug, held down by a shotglass.&amp;nbsp; Don't put the tyvek over the plug until the PC has cooled to below 15 psi though, as it's temperature sensitive.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8607597</next>\n<prev>8607494</prev>\n<first>8602765</first>\n<last>18368299</last>\n<when>1215531007</when>\n<utime>07/08/08 06:30 PM</utime>\n</post>"}